{"key":"processedPost-17097702","value":{"id":17097702,"first":17097542,"last":17114263,"when":1351175634,"utime":"10/25/12 05:33 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>Cultivatorian said:</strong><br />Could I use these??<br /><a href=\"http://www.grainger.com/Grainger/LAB-SAFETY-SUPPLY-Filter-12K926?Pid=search\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer noopener\">http://www.grainger.com/Grainger<wbr>/LAB-SAFETY-SUPPLY-Filter-12K926?<wbr>Pid=search</a></blockquote><br />Not suitable.<br />First, they're paper.&nbsp; That means they start to degrade when damp, which is going to happen in the pressure cooker.&nbsp; Second, they are also not temperature rated, which means the pore size changes during sterilization.&nbsp; Third, they will allow the mycelium to colonize them since they're not synthetic.&nbsp; Fourth, they are thin and will have the same problems as the filters on unicorn bags, which have an almost 100% failure rate due to faulty filters.<br />Synthetic filter disks are nearly 1/8\" thick, are synthetic so they don't degrade, and are heat resistant.&nbsp; They also can be had for less than 40 cents each, so I fail to see how that's so expensive considering they can be used and reused thousands of times.<br />RR","title":"Re: Synthetic filter disc"}}